	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Success factors for building small-scale initiatives in the Pacific</h1>

			
			<h4>
												29 October 2010
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>Oxfam has published a discussion paper examining case studies of mainly agriculture-based initiatives in five Pacific ACP states. The 14 case studies are drawn from Vanuatu (5), Papua New Guinea (4), Fiji (3), Tonga (1) and Samoa (1). They draw out the success factors that enabled the ventures to overcome serious production, infrastructural, marketing and cultural constraints typical of the Pacific region, and describe how the initiatives have successfully accessed special export markets offering premium prices that reflect the special characteristics of the final products of these ventures. The focus on enterprises within agriculture and agro-processing sectors is particularly important, given that the majority of the populations in Pacific countries derive their incomes from agriculture, much of it still within the informal sector. Key elements that enabled enterprises to overcome constraints included:</p>
<ul>

<li>use of IT, training and mobile phone services to address communication problems;</li>

<li>leveraging goods with a high value-to-weight ratio to benefit from cost-effective means of transportation; </li>

<li>adding value to products both in order to bypass quarantine restrictions on unprocessed commodities and to access higher-value markets; </li>

<li>developing innovative strategies to overcome irregularities in supply, e.g. offering growers higher prices and a consistent market.</li>

</ul>
<p>The report found that successfully accessing higher-value markets was achieved through niche marketing, through promoting the Pacific brand, and through ensuring quality. In addition, certification of products either as organic or fair-trade by recognised certification agencies ensured premium prices and a guarantee of access to overseas markets. Specific success factors to secure higher-value export markets included:</p>
<ul>

<li>the role of exporters and NGOs in linking growers to markets. Building a strong relationship between the exporters and the producers resulted in greater trust and increased frequency of interactions, which in turn led to an increase in investment, reflected in increased outputs and improved quality;</li>

<li>the importance of overseas travel to research the markets and link producers/growers with prospective buyers; </li>

</ul>
<p>Other key factors identified as contributing to the success of the ventures were:</p>
<ul>

<li>ensuring improvement of the producers’ incomes; </li>

<li>involvement of women in the economic enterprises. This was proven to work positively by strengthening these relationships;</li>

<li>the structure of producers’ groups, achieving different dynamics by working with individual households or with cooperatives; </li>

<li>the provision of training by the agricultural extension services, and other forms of training, such as in handicrafts, business skills, microfinance, and entrepreneurial activity. </li>

<li>the adding of value at the village level. This took processing away from a centralised depot to the farm gate, removing intermediary costs for the producers and leading to better returns, as well as improved quality of raw materials and longer storage life.</li>

</ul>
<p>All these factors were found to have contributed to both broad-based economic development in the communities and sustainable development, with ventures that were appropriate, that involved tradable products, and could be increased in scale.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>Oxfam, ‘Learning from experience: Sustainable economic development in the Pacific, <i>Oxfam Discussion Paper</i>, July 2010</p><p>
<a href="http://www.acp-eu-trade.org/library/files/COATESetal._EN_010710_Oxfam_Learningfromexp..pdf" target="_self">http://www.acp-eu-trade.org/library/files/COATESetal._EN_010710_Oxfam_Le...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The ventures studied in five Pacific ACP states have all become successful exporters of value-added agricultural products as a result of their owners/managers deliberately taking measures to overcome production and marketing constraints that typically affect producers in the region, including notably the small scale of production, scarcity of management skills, lack of infrastructure, distance from markets, and lack of competitiveness in the marketplace. However the capacity of governments in the region to provide an enabling environment was also found in the report to have been limited in recent decades ‘by structural adjustment programmes and other reforms’. While NGOs and donors played an important role, ‘they cannot supplant the vital role of governments’. One example of successful governmental support was a joint EU-French programme that sought to revitalise agricultural extension services and smallholder support. This kind of support would lead to an improved enabling environment, and enhancing exports and more broad-based economic development.</p><p>The report provides a good coverage of the wide range of success factors of the 14 ventures. However it underlines the importance of ‘government and external support for important economic infrastructure’, such as ‘the development of internal markets, agricultural extension services, improved access to market information, minimising the disadvantages from transport and communications, and technical and business skills development training.’ Extending the provision of an enabling environment to all producers is a significant challenge for any developing country where resource constraint is a major concern.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
